marked =0Aat $22 billion (actually down 30%) or at $15.5 billion=3F Meanwhi=
le there was =0Atalk about the banks who loaned him the $13 billion also ma=
rking down the value =0Aof their debt significantly, which implied a very l=
ow valuation for the equity.=0A=0ABut recently those banks have been sellin=
g the debt <> at around par, and now =0Ahere=E2=80=99s this <>:=0A=0AElon M=
usk=E2=80=99s X is in talks to raise money from investors at a $44 billion =
=0Avaluation, according to people familiar with the matter. That is the sam=
e price =0Athat Musk paid for the social media company in 2022, when it was=
 called Twitter.=0A=0AThe funding round would be a remarkable turn of fortu=
nes for the company after =0AMusk=E2=80=99s takeover and overhaul caused ma=
ny users and advertisers to flee. In =0ADecember, prior to the current deal=
 talks, Fidelity Investments had marked down =0Aits Twitter stake by about =
70% from the 2022 sale price.=0A=0AI assume that=E2=80=99s a $44 billion en=
terprise value =E2=80=94 flat to what he paid for it =E2=80=94 =0Abut if th=
e equity that he bought for $31 billion is now worth $44 billion, =0Athat=
=E2=80=99s a good trade. It would be reductive to say =E2=80=9Cwith his $44=
 billion =0Apurchase of Twitter, Elon Musk secured absolute control over th=
e US =0Agovernment,=E2=80=9D but even if you think that that is, like, 1% t=
rue, it=E2=80=99s probably =0Aworth $44 billion.=0A=0A=0AMeta-fiduciary dut=
ies=0A=0AThere are two typical ways to get financial advice in the US. You =
can go to a =0Abroker, who will give you some suggestions on what stocks or=
 mutual funds to =0Abuy, and who will typically get paid out of commissions=
 (you pay her some money =0Aeach time you trade) and/or by the companies wh=
ose products she sells. Or you =0Acan go to a financial adviser, who will g=
enerally provide comprehensive =0Ainvestment advice and typically charge yo=
u an annual fee that is some =0Apercentage of your assets, often 1%. Histor=
ically financial advisers had a =0Afiduciary duty to act in your best inter=
ests, while brokers could be pretty =0Amercenary, butsince 2019 <> retail b=
rokers also have an obligation <> to act in =0Ayour best interest when they=
 recommend investments.=0A=0AStill, there is a lingering stereotype that br=
okers are out to make as much =0Amoney as possible off of you, while fiduci=
ary advisers are looking out for you =0Aand happy with their 1%. If your br=
oker is calling you up every week with some =0Anew complicated structured p=
roduct, putting you into new trades constantly, and =0Acharging fees each t=
ime, she is probably making more than 1% per year off of =0Ayou. On the oth=
er hand, if you are just in some index funds, and your broker =0Acalls you =
once a month with a trade idea and you say =E2=80=9Cno thanks, I=E2=80=99m =
good with =0Amy index funds,=E2=80=9D she is probably making less than 1% p=
er year.=0A=0AAnd so if (1) you are boring and steady and (2) your broker i=
s greedy, there =0Ais a natural tradefor your broker. The trade is: Become =
your financial adviser =0Aand start charging you 1% per year. [9]  <> There=
 are problems with this trade, =0Athough:=0A=0A * You have to agree to it, =
and =E2=80=9Cpay me 1% of your account every year for the =0Asame service y=
ou=E2=80=99re getting now=E2=80=9D is a tough sell. The broker might have t=
o hide =0Athat in the fine print. =0A * Your broker does have some obligati=
on to act in your best interests (before =0Aand after you convert to an adv=
isory account), and =E2=80=9Cpay me 1% of your account =0Aevery year for th=
e same service=E2=80=9D does not seem to be in your best interests=3F =0AAn=
yway on Jan. 21 I wrote <> =E2=80=9Cwhat if the US Securities and Exchange =
=0ACommission never brings another enforcement case,=E2=80=9D and I wasn=E2=
=80=99tthat serious, =0Abut I was alittle serious. But here is the first SE=
C enforcement press release =0A<> of the second Trump administration [10]  =
<>:=0A=0AThe Securities and Exchange Commission [Friday] filed settled char=
ges against =0ANew York-based registered investment adviser One Oak Capital=
 Management LLC, =0Aand former One Oak investment adviser representative, M=
ichael DeRosa, for =0Amisconduct related to advisory services provided to t=
heir retail clients.=0A=0AAccording to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, from approx=
imately June 2020 through October =0A2023, One Oak and DeRosa recommended t=
hat DeRosa=E2=80=99s customers at an unaffiliated =0Abroker-dealer, at whic=
h he was simultaneously employed, convert more than 180 =0Abrokerage accoun=
ts to advisory accounts at One Oak. Most of these customers =0Awere elderly=
 and had been long-time customers of DeRosa=E2=80=99s at the broker-dealer,=
 =0Awhich charged the customers on a commission basis. According to the ord=
er, One =0AOak and DeRosa ignored their fiduciary duty and failed to adequa=
tely disclose =0Athat the conversions from brokerage accounts to advisory a=
ccounts would result =0Ain significantly higher fees for the clients and in=
creased compensation for =0ADeRosa; nor did they disclose the resulting con=
flict of interest. The order =0Afinds that the change in fee structure resu=
lted in significantly increased =0Acosts, but the clients generally receive=
d no additional services or benefits. =0AThe order further finds that One O=
ak and DeRosa failed to adequately consider =0Awhether it was in their clie=
nts=E2=80=99 best interests to convert their brokerage =0Aaccounts to advis=
ory accounts, and in fact, many of the accounts were not =0Asuitable to be =
advisory accounts.=0A=0AFrom the SEC=E2=80=99s order <>:=0A=0AFor example, =
the accounts converted in 2020 and 2021 incurred a more than =0Aseven-fold =
increase in fees and costs on average, and some clients paid more =0Athan t=
en times in advisory fees to One Oak as they had paid in commissions to =0A=
the broker-dealer over a similar time period.=0A=0ADespite the higher fees =
charged to the Converted Accounts, DeRosa did not =0Asignificantly alter th=
e trading activity of the accounts following the =0Aconversions to advisory=
 accounts, or generally provide additional services to =0Athese accounts. W=
hile the accounts were brokerage accounts at the =0Abroker-dealer, DeRosa h=
ad discretionary authority to trade in the accounts, and =0Ahe executed rel=
atively few trades=E2=80=94approximately one transaction per two months =0A=
per account, on average. After the conversions to advisory accounts, DeRosa=
 did =0Anot significantly increase the trading activity in the Converted Ac=
counts. In =0Asome instances, the number of transactions post-conversion de=
creased =0Asignificantly because DeRosa did not obtain the necessary author=
izations from =0Aclients to execute options trading strategies he had previ=
ously employed at the =0Abroker-dealer. Many of the Converted Accounts had =
few, if any, trades for more =0Athan a year after their conversion to advis=
ory accounts.=0A=0AWell, yes, right, the best accounts for a broker are the=
 ones that trade a =0Alot, and the best accounts for a financial adviser ar=
e the ones that never =0Atrade. For the customer, it=E2=80=99s the opposite=
.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0AFirst-Day IPO Trading Flops <> Threaten Next =
Wave of US Debuts. Anglo American =0ASellsNickel Business <> for Up to $500=
 Million. Nikola <>, Once a Darling of =0AGreen Investment, Files for Bankr=
uptcy. Lingering Question at Coinbase: Who =0AReally Ownsthe Customers=E2=
=80=99 Crypto <>=3F Who is the bad art adviser <>=3F Milei =0ACrypto Scanda=
l <> Widens With Allegations Against His Sister. =0A=0AIf you'd like to get=
 Money Stuff in handy email form, right in your inbox, =0Apleasesubscribe a=
t this link <>. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other =0Agreat Bloo=
mberg newslettershere <>. Thanks!=0A=0A[1] I think it is not quite accurate=
 to say =E2=80=9Cthe shareholders of a company own =0Athat company,=E2=80=
=9D andcorporate law theorists <> will get annoyed by this, but it=E2=80=99=
s =0Aa useful shorthand that most shareholders and executives tend to belie=
ve.=0A=0A[2] I take this idea from Patrick McKenzie, who writes <>: =E2=80=
=9CI bought the stock =0A[of MGM Resorts International] for the same reason=
 I buy stock in every hotel, =0Aairline, bank, and similar I use: in the un=
likely event a =0Anot-particularly-high-stakes poker player has a routine c=
ustomer service =0Acomplaint, Investor Relations is available as an escalat=
ion strategy, over e.g. =0Ahotel staff who might be long-since inured to li=
stening to complaints from =0Apeople who lost money in a casino.=E2=80=9D=
=0A=0A[3] Is governance too left-wing=3F I have  never understood this one =
<>; it=E2=80=99s =0Anot obvious that wanting public companies to separate t=
he role of board chair =0Aand chief executive officer is particularly left-=
wing. That said, if you are a =0Aconservative and you think that corporate =
managers are less left-wing than big =0Aasset managers, you might prefer =
=E2=80=9Cworse governance=E2=80=9D: You might want to insulate =0ACEOs from=
 shareholder pressures, because the shareholder pressures would push =0Athe=
m to the left. There is also the somewhat odd contingency that Elon Musk an=
d =0ADonald Trump are the main leaders of the US right wing, and they are b=
oth sort =0Aof governance messes, so being in favor of traditional good gov=
ernance reads as =0Aan anti-Musk-and-Trump position.=0A=0A[4] In particular=
, if you invest money in a hedge fund that charges 2-and-20 =0Afees, in a s=
ense you really are paying a premium.=0A=0A[5] That still appears to be its=
 official name=3F =E2=80=9CMicroStrategy Incorporated =0Ad/b/a Strategy <>=
=E2=80=9D=3F =0A=0A[6] And, it goes almost without saying, more than the un=
derlying Bitcoin *plus =0Athe operating business* is worth. The operating b=
usiness can in many cases be =0Apretty vestigial.=0A=0A[7] This is loose, b=
ecause a lot of Berkshire is in private companies so it=E2=80=99s =0Ahard t=
o compute NAV.=0A=0A[8] Or  QXO <> is roughly an investment fund that trade=
s at a premium, and it =0Awas built out of the shell of a software company =
called SilverSun.=0A=0A[9] And in fact, one concern about the relatively ne=
w rules requiring brokers =0Ato consider their retail customers=E2=80=99 be=
st interests was that imposing fiduciary =0Aduties on brokers would push br=
okers to stop offering commission-only brokerage =0Aaccounts and instead of=
fer only fee-based advisory accounts, which would make =0Ait harder and mor=
e expensive for (some) retail customers to get brokerage =0Aaccounts with a=
 little bit of financial advice. See, e.g., footnote 33 tothe =0Afinal Regu=
lation Best Interests rule <>, discussing the effects of an earlier =0ADepa=
rtment of Labor rule imposing fiduciary duties on some retail brokers: =E2=
=80=9CA =0Anumber of industry studies indicated that, as a result of the DO=
L Fiduciary =0ARule, industry participants had already or were planning to =
alter services and =0Aproducts available to retail customers. For example, =
of the 21 members of the =0ASecurities Industry and Financial Markets Assoc=
iation (=E2=80=98SIFMA=E2=80=99) that =0Aparticipated in the SIFMA Study, 5=
3% eliminated or reduced access to brokerage =0Aadvice services and 67% mig=
rated away from open choice to fee-based or limited =0Abrokerage services.=
